						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">People generally don't want to make games if they think it will be hard to make carts of them, and nobody wants to create mappers for which no games exist... I imagine that games have to come first</div><br />And these games might be PC prototypes written in C++ or C# or Python (pygame/pyglet) or something. Can Lua in FCEUX simulate missing mapper features?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">my personal opinion is that your game must have an actual necessity for the mapper's features. You must use extended attributes</div>
<br />And even I found a way around a requirement for extended attributes in an otherwise-NROM game. At first I thought I'd have to use extended attributes to make a grid of 8x8 pixel tiles with arbitrary colors, but <a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?p=45685#45685" class="postlink">Drag and I ended up figuring out how to use dithered 3-color tiles</a> and keep it NROM.</div>

